Replaces Record Ids

(id)

Datatype

SET<II>

Set of Identifier (Unique collection; each occurrence includes id, assigning authority)

Conformance

Required

Implementers must support, but only supply data when it is available

Repetitions

Unlimited

Number of repetitions are unlimited

 

 

 

Description

Used to identify any records that are "superceded" by the current record. This will cause the referenced records to be marked as "obsolete" with a reference pointing to this record.

Rationale

Used in circumstances where information initially captured about an event is erroneous, incomplete or not captured at the desired level of detail and the change cannot be made by retracting the original record. (E.g. Too much time has elapsed, change is being made by a provider other than the original author of the vent record, etc.) May also be used to reference multiple records in the case where the same event has been accidentally captured more than once.

Patient

(Subject22)

Description

This identifies the patient associated with the Care Composition

Rationale

Used to link the record to the patient's EHR and is therefore mandatory.

The repetition of 100 is to allow for the specification of an encounter involving a group of persons.

In circumstances where number of patients involved is greater than the limit supported by the message, multiple encounters should be used.

R_AssignedEntityUniversal (COCT_MT090000)

AssignedEntity

(ResponsibleParty)

Description

This identifies the person or organization that has primary responsibility for the actions of the author in creating the Care Composition. The supervising provider is not necessarily present when the action is performed, but is professionally accountable for the action through the power to delegate, and the duty to review actions with the performing actor after the fact.

Rationale

Needed in circumstances where one provider is acting under the professional authority of another. E.g. Pharmacy technician under pharmacist, resident under supervising physician, etc.

Tracking responsibility is essential for authorization and regulatory purposes. It also provides a secondary person to contact for follow-up.

Implementation

If not specified, it is assumed that the author is acting under their own professional authority. I.e. If the author and supervisor are the same, only the author should be sent.

ProviderOrPatientOrRelated

(Informant)

Description

Rationale

Understanding the source of data is essential to its interpretation. It can be very valuable to include information in the EHR that has been reported to the recording provider by the patient, patient's relative or other person. However, it is equally important that such information be clearly distinguished from information of which the provider has first-hand awareness.

Implementation

If not specified, it is assumed that the author is capturing information of which they have first-hand awareness.

R_ResponsiblePartyUniversal (COCT_MT040200)

AssignedEntity

(Performer3)

Description

Identifies the person who actually performed the action described in the record.

For outpatient encounters, identifies the provider(s) with principle responsibility for the encounter. For inpatient/institutional encounters, this generally isn't used (admitting and discharge providers are captured elsewhere).

For episodes and care events, identifies the providers currently responsible for managing the episode or type of care (may change over time).

NOTE: This is *not* intended to capture all providers involved in care, merely those responsible for care. In most circumstances this will only be one provider. However, in some circumstances (e.g. telehealth) it may be necessary to capture more than one.

In circumstances where number of providers involved is greater than the limit supported by the message, multiple encounters should be used.

Rationale

The person who makes the decision to capture information in the electronic record is not always the person who actually performed the action. Knowledge of the performer is useful both for tracking responsibility and for subsequent follow-up.

Multiple repetitions are allowed for those circumstances where more than one provider is involved.

Implementation

If not specified, it is assumed that the author is also the performer. I.e. If the author and performer are the same, only the author should be sent. If the author is not the performer, but the performer is not known, a null flavor of UNK (unknown) should be used.

AssignedEntity

(Author2)

Description

This identifies the provider who requested the Care Composition to be performed. The request may have been verbal, electronic, as part of a referral or by other means. This element does not need to be captured in "record" and "update" messages where a request id is captured, as the requesting provider can be looked up by retrieving the request. Also known as the "Admitting Provider"

Requested by provider is only relevant in the context of encounters. It should not be used for Episodes or Care Events.

Admitting provider is only relevant in a hospital setting or other institutional setting (e.g. nursing home, long-term care, etc.)

Rationale

By requesting the action, the provider takes a level of responsibility for it. The attribute may also be used to search or filter records. Requesting providers generally have authorization to view masked information as well.

ActChoice

(Reason)

Description

Identifies the clinical reason(s) for the creation of the Care Composition.

Rationale

Essential for understanding the context in which the action was performed. Also frequently used in searching and filtering and can impact whether the record will be automatically masked. Multiple indications are supported for circumstances where the Care Composition is being done for multiple reasons.

Implementation

Rationale

Used in circumstances where information initially captured about an event is erroneous, incomplete or not captured at the desired level of detail and the change cannot be made by retracting the original record. (E.g. Too much time has elapsed, change is being made by a provider other than the original author of the vent record, etc.) May also be used to reference multiple records in the case where the same event has been accidentally captured more than once.

Participant Groupings

(Component2)

Description

Identifies components of the overall encounter that happened at each location.

Rationale

Allows distinguishing which providers and patients were involved in each location. This is an optional element as not all systems will necessarily capture this type of information. It is primarily useful for telehealth-type applications.

Participants

(Participant)

Description

Identifies the participants associated with the particular location.

Rationale

Important for providing context for the encounter. The element is mandatory because there whole purpose of having a participant grouping is to have participants.

Attributes

Participant Id Reference

(role.id)

Datatype

II

Identifier (includes id, assigning authority)

Conformance

Mandatory

Value must always be supplied (no nulls)

Repetitions

1

Does not repeat

 

 

 

Description

The unique identifier of a patient or provider who was involved in the encounter at the identified location. This will reference one of the patient or provider ids already associated with the Care Composition.

Rationale

Links the participant to the location where they were involved in the encounter. The element is mandatory because there's no point listing participants unless they can be explicitly identified.

Description

Identifies how the patient and/or provider(s) participated in the encounter (in person, by phone, by videoconference, etc.)

Rationale

Understanding how each participant was involved in the encounter gives context to the encounter, particularly for telehealth.

 

Participant Confidentiality

(role.confidentialityCode)

Datatype

SET<CV>

Set of Code (Unique collection; each occurrence includes mnemonic, code-system and original text)

Conformance

Optional

Implementers may declare whether they support the concept or not

Repetitions

Unlimited

Number of repetitions are unlimited

Code Strength

CNE

Must be coded using 'official' codeset (no un-coded text or local codes)

Code Domain

Confidentiality

 

 

 

Description

Identifies the confidentiality level associated with the encounter for this specific participant.

Rationale

Provides individual participants in a group encounter with complete control over the confidentiality of their participation in that encounter.

The attribute is optional because not all systems will support masking.

Implementation

This element should only be specified if the id is referencing a patient, not a provider.

Stricter confidentiality asserted at the overall encounter level overrides looser confidentiality asserted at the participant level.
